                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4 font-medium">Type N</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">
                        General above-grade walls, chimneys
                      </td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">1 : 3</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4 font-medium">Type S</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">Structural, below-grade, patios</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">1 : 2.25 (rounded to 1 : 2.3)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4 font-medium">Type M</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">High-strength, foundations</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">1 : 2.5</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4 font-medium">Type O</td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">
                        Low-strength, interior, restoration
                      </td>
                      <td class="py-1 pr-4">1 : 4</td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you are using separate portland cement, lime and sand,
                consult the manufacturer or local code for the correct
                three-part ratio (e.g. 1:1:6 for Type N) and adjust the
                equivalent cement:sand ratio accordingly.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Estimating mortar volume from wall dimensions</h3>
              <p>
                When you choose <strong>“Estimate from wall size”</strong>, the
                calculator:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Computes the wall area from length and height.</li>
                <li>
                  Computes the face area of a single unit (brick or block).
                </li>
                <li>Estimates how many units fit in the wall area.</li>
                <li>
                  Approximates the mortar volume per unit based on joint
                  thickness and wall thickness.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>The total mortar volume is then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>Net mortar volume</strong> ≈ (number of units) ×
                  (average joint volume per unit)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is an approximation, but it is usually more accurate than
                simple “bags per 100 bricks” rules because it accounts for your
                actual unit size and joint thickness.
              </p>

              <h3>3. From volume to bag counts</h3>
              <p>
                Once the net mortar volume is known, the calculator adds your
                chosen waste percentage:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>Gross volume</strong> = Net volume × (1 + waste% /
                  100)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Then it divides by the yield per bag:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>Bags required</strong> = Gross volume ÷ Yield per bag
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                You can override the default yield per bag with the value
                published on your specific product (for example, many 80 lb bags
                of mortar mix yield about 0.7 ft³ of mortar).
              </p>

              <h3>4. Cement, sand and water quantities</h3>
              <p>
                For site-mixed mortar, the calculator also shows the split
                between cement and sand by volume. If the total dry mortar
                volume is \( V_{\text{dry}} \) and the ratio is \( 1 : r \)
                (cement : sand), then:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  Cement volume = \( \dfrac{V_{\text{dry}}}{1 + r} \)
                  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sand volume = \( \dfrac{r \cdot
                  V_{\text{dry}}}{1 + r} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Water is estimated from the number of bags using a typical range
                (for example, 4–6 quarts per 80 lb bag). Always follow the
                manufacturer’s instructions on the bag and adjust on site for
                temperature, humidity and workability.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for mixing mortar</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use clean, potable water and well-graded, clean masonry sand.
                </li>
                <li>Mix dry ingredients thoroughly before adding water.</li>
                <li>
                  Add water gradually; it is easy to add more, but impossible to
                  remove excess.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Mortar should be workable and hold its shape on a trowel
                  without slumping.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only mix as much as you can place within 2 hours (or the time
                  specified by the manufacturer).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Protect fresh mortar from freezing, rapid drying and heavy
                  rain.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations & disclaimer</h3>
              <p>
                This calculator is intended for preliminary estimating only.
                Actual mortar requirements depend on workmanship, unit
                tolerances, joint profile, retempering, substrate absorption and
                many other factors. Always verify mix proportions and material
                quantities with the product data sheet, local building codes and
                a qualified professional for critical or structural work.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">Mortar mix FAQ</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is the standard mortar mix ratio?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For general above-grade brickwork, a common choice is Type N
                    mortar, often mixed at about 1:1:6 (cement:lime:sand by
                    volume) or simplified to roughly 1:3 cement to sand when
                    using masonry cement. Stronger mixes like Type S and Type M
                    use more cement relative to sand. Always follow local codes
                    and the manufacturer’s recommendations for your project.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How many bags of mortar do I need per 100 bricks?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    As a rule of thumb, one 80 lb bag of mortar mix will lay
                    about 35–40 standard modular bricks with 3/8 in joints. That
                    works out to roughly 2.5–3 bags per 100 bricks. The
                    calculator on this page refines that estimate using your
                    exact brick size and wall dimensions.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Can I use concrete mix instead of mortar mix?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    No. Concrete mix contains coarse aggregate (gravel) and is
                    not suitable for thin joints between bricks or blocks.
                    Mortar mix uses only fine aggregate (sand) and is formulated
                    for bond and workability. Use mortar for laying masonry
                    units and concrete for slabs, footings and structural
                    elements as specified by your design and local code.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How accurate is this mortar mix calculator?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For typical residential projects with standard units and
                    joints, this calculator will usually get you within about
                    10–20% of actual usage, which is why a waste factor is
                    included. For critical projects, unusual units or very large
                    jobs, confirm quantities with a detailed takeoff or a
                    professional estimator.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
